{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17592684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17592684"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:18:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:18:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15275"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15275","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15275"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.05,0.68,0,0.26]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7966"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65948"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7966"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15275"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51397"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8746"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19386"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22039"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65948","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65948"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECoeliac disease is an immune-mediated enteropathy triggered by exposure to dietary gluten in genetically predisposed individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the histological changes seen in the untreated disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased intraepithelial lymphocytes","Elongated intestinal villi","Increased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria","Normal goblet cell numbers","Reduced crypt depth"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn coeliac disease, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased inflammatory cells in the lamina propria\u003C/strong\u003E include plasma cells, lymphocytes, macrophages, eosinophils, and mast cells. This inflammatory infiltrate is a key diagnostic feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERather than showing \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased intraepithelial lymphocytes\u003C/strong\u003E, coeliac disease is characterised by increased numbers of these cells. Rather than being \u003Cstrong\u003Eelongated, intestinal villi\u003C/strong\u003E actually become blunted and may be completely flat. Crypts show hyperplasia and elongation and not any \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduced crypt depth\u003C/strong\u003E.  While \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal goblet cell numbers\u003C/strong\u003E might occasionally be seen, goblet cells are typically decreased in active disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional features include increased epithelial cell turnover and damage to the brush border, leading to malabsorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coeliac disease causes characteristic villous atrophy and crypt hyperplasia in the proximal small intestine","The lamina propria in coeliac disease shows increased inflammatory cells including plasma cells, lymphocytes, and eosinophils","Coeliac disease is triggered by gluten exposure in genetically susceptible individuals"],"references":["DuPont HL. Persistent Diarrhea: A Clinical Review. JAMA. 2016 Jun 28;315(24):2712-23. doi: 10.1001/jama.2016.7833. PMID: 27357241","Nemeth V, Pfleghaar N. Diarrhea. [Updated 2022 Nov 21]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448082/","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D